^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Good try. contract could not be made. We will discuss the play in a minute, but first lets analyze the bidding. I would not criticize North for passing 2N but I think that is pessimistic. I hate playing 2N voluntarily. Basically, it is only right when you make exactly 2N, not 3N. So, I tend to strain to bid over 2N openers and I agree with Eileen's bidding. It turns out 4H is not a bad contract. You have two red suit losers so if you can hold your black suit losers to 1, you make the hand. That means if Barbara has at least two black honors, the hand makes. Essentially, I am saying the hand is on two of thee finesses. It turns out (although it is certainly not obvious) that the odds of that happening are 50 percent.|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Basically, the 4 possibilities are:
1) all the finesses win 
2) two finesses win 
3) one finesse wins 
4) no finesses win. 
Therefore, in two of four possibilities, you make the hand. Hence the odds of two of three finesses (at least) working is 50%.  know that sounds strange, but it is true.|
