^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let me discuss the strip and endplay a bit further. The basic idea is you get rid of all the side suits, ruffing if necessary, and throw the non-dangerous opponent into the lead. In this case, South  is the non-dangerous opponent. By stripping the hand of clubs and hearts, Barbara made it impossible for South  to lead those suits without giving a ruff and sluff. And then by throwing South  in with a diamond, if South  leads another diamond, Barbara's king is good no matter who has the Ace. On this hand, since North  had the Ace of diamonds it did not matter, but if South  had the Ace of diamonds, it would have made a big difference. For those interested, I have a lesson on end plays, in my declarer lesson play series.|
