^-{  When to Lead Trumps - Marty Bergen/Howard Schutzman  }
^-|
CP||fp||at|^C@2^z@3There are many auctions which scream for trump leads. Here are some of the most common: |
PG| ***** 121 ***** |


AT|

^*B1. ^DDummy denied support for the major suit that declarer opened.^*N
Responder must have fewer than 3 cards (0, 1, or 2) in opener's major. You can almost see dummy's short suit. Once you do, a trump lead is almost always best.|
PG| ***** 122 ***** |


AT|

^*B2. ^DThe opponents sacrifice.^*N 
When the opponents sacrifice, almost always lead trump–-even with a singleton. You say that you were taught not to lead a singleton trump. That's good advice-–in general. However, when the declaring side has limited strength, trump leads are the way to go.|
PG| ***** 123 ***** |


AT|

^*B3. ^DYour side has strength in all of the side suits.^*N 
Sometimes, the opponents bid game when you know they can't have more than half the deck, and your side has shown values in all of the side suits. How did they justify bidding game? There can be only one answer – distribution. Neither he nor dummy can have a strong suit that can be used to discard losers. Your mission is clear. Lead trumps early and often.|
PG| ***** 124 ***** |


AT|

^*B4. ^DWhen your side opens 1NT, and you are on lead against a 2-suited auction, such as DONT or Cappelletti. ^*N
The opponents are playing in a suit because at least one of them has shape. They want to ruff your high cards; you don't want them to.|
PG| ***** 125 ***** |


AT|

^*B5. ^DPartner passes your takeout double of an opening bid of 1C or 1D.^*N 
Partner's "once every year and a half" pass of your one-level takeout double can only be based on a massive holding in opener's suit. Once you help partner remove the opponents' trumps, your strength in the other suits will allow your side to be in control. Next is an example where your side has strength in all side suits.|
